News - PRIISM - NYU Steinhardt                                                                         NYU Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development       PRIISM Center for the Promotion of Research Involving Innovative Statistical Methodology                                      News                                                                   10.15.13: New volume published: "Sage Handbook of Multilevel Modeling," edited by PRIISM Co-Director, M. Scott, NYU Stern Prof. J. Simonoff & LSU Prof. B. Marx, with c ontributions by PRIISM Center faculty: J. Buckley, M. Harada, Co-Director J. Hill, M. Scott, Z. Townsend, S. Weinberg, and NYU Psychology Prof. P. Shrout. More details given here .    8.28.13: New/updated applied statistical methods courses of interest to the PRIISM Center community offered Fall 2013/Spring 2014    The PRIISM Center would like to highlight two new courses being offered Fall 2013 and two being offered Spring 2014 that may be of interest to you or your students.       FALL 2013 :    RESCH-GE 2016 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods – Factor Scoring and Practical Issues in Scaling (Informal title, "Measurement in the Trenches" -- 2 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Fall 2013; Mondays 4:55-7:35pm; course runs in the second half of the term, beginning Oct. 29. This course was created in response to inquiries from students and faculty regarding methodological challenges with measurement and scaling. It expands on the topics of measurement and reliability discussed in introductory courses. The focus is how to do factor analysis in settings where test/questionnaire data has already been collected and a method for getting scores from those data is required. It is intended to provide students with the requisite skills to deal with this kind of problem in their own research. Topics include: basics of matrix algebra, distinguishing among different factor models (e.g., principal components, principal axis), methods of factor scoring, assessing goodness of fit, how and why to rotate a factor solution, how to deal with dichotomous and ordered categorical (e.g., Likert) data, and special issues that arise in cross-group and cross-cultural applications (e.g., floor and ceiling effects, measurement invariance). Class time is split between 1/3 theoretical discussion and 2/3 hands-on examples using STATA and R statistical software. Readings will be drawn from journal articles. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/RESCH-GE_2016.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------          At Stern IOMS:       GB 4310.01 Statistics for Social Data; meets Wednesdays 2:00-5:00pm. Instructor: Patrick Perry    Statistical methods for describing and utilizing nontraditional data modalities arising from social processes. Half of the course will be devoted to network data (communications, recommendations, and transactions) and the other half will be devoted to textual data (words, phrases, and documents). We will survey a broad class of models for dealing with these types of data. Possible topics include the following: word-sense disambiguation; sentiment analysis; Markov and hidden Markov text models; topic discovery; descriptive statistics for networks; community detection; exponential random graph models; latent space models; network sampling; point processes; low-rank matrix approximations; power laws. See here for a syllabus. Contact pperry@stern.nyu.edu for more details.       -----------------------------------------------------------------------       SPRING 2014:          APSTA-GE 2094 Factor Analysis and Structural Equation Modeling (3 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Spring 2014; Wednesdays 3:30-6:10pm. Course provides students with the software skills and theoretical knowledge required to apply structural equation modeling (SEM). First, we review of multiple regression and basic concepts from matrix algebra. Next, path analysis and factor analysis are developed, leading to more advanced topics, including how to translate theory into models, strategies for dealing with poor fitting specifications, categorical data, and issues in multigroup analysis. The latter component focuses on data applications of SEM, including a final project. Example material will be drawn from education and psychology. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA-GE_2094_Sp2014.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------      APSTA-GE 2997 Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research: Generalized Linear Models (2 points) Instructor: Ying Lu Spring 2014; F 9:30-12:30 (course meets the second half of the term) This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples are drawn from broad areas of health and policy research including determinants of self-reported health status or factors influencing number of clinic visits. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA_2997_syllabus_2014.pdf            12.7.12: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2013       NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2004 Advanced Modeling I: Topics in Multivariate Analysis meets Tuesdays 3:30-6:00pm, Jan 29-Mar 12 (one hour lab follows lecture). Instructor: Peter Halpin.    This year, STRUCTURAL EQUATION MODELS ARE EMPHASIZED. Examines some of the more advanced topics in multivariate data analysis for the behavioral, social, and health sciences. The focus is structural equation modeling with latent variables, although we build up to this topic by considering path analysis, principal components analysis, exploratory factor analysis, and confirmatory factor analysis. Other topics are also surveyed (e.g., MANOVA). The software package STATA is used to give students hands-on experience with analyzing data using the methods covered in class. In so doing, the course provides skills and knowledge critical to those graduate students whose research relies on the analysis of quantitative data. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2042.    12.7.12: Courses offered biennially, offered THIS Spring 2013    NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2011 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods: Classification & Clustering. Meets Fri 9:30am-12:00pm (course begins Mar 26). Instructor: Marc Scott.     Classification and clustering are important statistical techniques commonly applied in many social and behavioral science research problems. Both seek to understand social phenomena through the identification of naturally occurring homogeneous groupings within a population. Classification techniques are used to sort new observations into pre-existing or known groupings, while clustering techniques sort the population under study into groupings based on their observed characteristics. They are sometimes referred to as supervised and unsupervised learning. This course will introduce the student to both techniques, emphasizing visualization, algorithms and models, particulalry for clustering, including the latent class model known as Nagin clusters. May be taken concurrently with any of the other offerings. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2011.       NYU Course # PSYCH-GA 2248 Analysis of Change. Monday 12:00-1:50PM (lecture); Lab session TBA Instructor Patrick Shrout.  This course will review current issues and methods involving the analysis of change in the behavioral and social sciences. Starting from classical methods for the analysis of change (change scores, mixed model ANOVA, regression and MANOVA), we examine the rationale and utility of newer methods: Generalized estimating equations (GEE), Latent change approaches, Hierarchical linear (multilevel) models, and survival analysis. The methods will be introduced conceptually and will be illustrated using real and simulated data. Prior year's syllabus available here: http://www.psych.nyu.edu/couples/Shrout/Syllabi/index.html    NYU Course # SOC-GA 3306 Event History Analysis. Meets Weds 6:20-9PM. Instructor: Lawrence Wu.    This course surveys methods for analyzing event history data, with a focus on continuous-time models and estimation techniques. Topics include the exploratory analysis of event history data, nonparametric methods, right censoring, maximum likelihood estimation, alternative specifications for a time dependent baseline hazard rate, observed and unobserved heterogeneity, time-varying covariates, proportional and nonproportional models, multiple transition and competing risk models, left truncation and left censoring, and analogs of recursive and nonrecursive models. Major emphasis is placed on the logic, practical use, and estimation of models. Prior syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/SOC-GA-3306_syl.pdf    12.6.12: [NYC/Columbia Univ.] META-ANALYSIS COURSE - Spring 2013    TC Course # HUDM 5130 Meta-analysis meets Tuesdays 3:00-5:00pm. Instructor: L. Elizabeth Tipton    This course introduces methods for conducting a quantitative research synthesis using meta-analysis. The focus of the course is both practical and methodological and includes background on all parts of the research synthesis process, including: problem formulation, conducting a literature search, data evaluation, effect size coding, data analysis, and reporting the results. Additionally, the statistical methods used for summarizing the effects found in a study (effect sizes) and for combining the results of these studies under different models (meta-analysis) are introduced and developed. Contact tipton@tc.columbia.edu for more details.       12.3.11: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2012    Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research (Biostatistics III)    NYU Course # RESCH-GE.2997 Meets Mondays, 4:45 – 7:35pm 3 points    This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples include health status, number of clinic visits, etc. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses.    Current syllabus here .    Please contact the course instructor, Ying Lu (ying.lu@nyu.edu) with any questions.    Measurement: Modern Test Theory    NYU Course # APSY-GE.2141 Meets Wednesdays, 3:30 – 6:10pm 3 points    All graduate students from all schools are welcome to enroll. Course requires comfort with introductory statistics and a willingness to learn some statistical programming.    Examines the principles of psychological measurement and testing and the technical interpretation of test scores using modern test models, including Item Response Theory, with an emphasis on the Rasch model. Considers matters of reliability and validity as related to modern test theory. Emphasizes the application of test theory to computerized and/or adaptive testing. Utilizes statistical software to conduct analyses. This course is recommended for anyone with an interest in developing, evaluating and analyzing surveys and assessments related to education, the social sciences, and medicine. Recent syllabus here ; flyer here .    Please contact the course instructor, Jeffrey Steedle (jsteedle@nyu.edu) with any questions.    A listing of applied statistics courses (and many syllabi) offered at Steinhardt and related departments at NYU is given here , here and here .       9.2.11: [NYC/Columbia Univ.] BAYESIAN COMPUTING COURSE - Fall 2011 Andrew Gelman , Columbia University Professor of Statistics & Political Science, will be teaching a graduate seminar this fall that might be of interest to students. The course is centered on several active research projects in Bayesian computing. News - PRIISM - NYU Steinhardt                                                                         NYU Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development       PRIISM Center for the Promotion of Research Involving Innovative Statistical Methodology                                      News                                                                   10.15.13: New volume published: "Sage Handbook of Multilevel Modeling," edited by PRIISM Co-Director, M. Scott, NYU Stern Prof. J. Simonoff & LSU Prof. B. Marx, with c ontributions by PRIISM Center faculty: J. Buckley, M. Harada, Co-Director J. Hill, M. Scott, Z. Townsend, S. Weinberg, and NYU Psychology Prof. P. Shrout. More details given here .    8.28.13: New/updated applied statistical methods courses of interest to the PRIISM Center community offered Fall 2013/Spring 2014    The PRIISM Center would like to highlight two new courses being offered Fall 2013 and two being offered Spring 2014 that may be of interest to you or your students.       FALL 2013 :    RESCH-GE 2016 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods – Factor Scoring and Practical Issues in Scaling (Informal title, "Measurement in the Trenches" -- 2 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Fall 2013; Mondays 4:55-7:35pm; course runs in the second half of the term, beginning Oct. 29. This course was created in response to inquiries from students and faculty regarding methodological challenges with measurement and scaling. It expands on the topics of measurement and reliability discussed in introductory courses. The focus is how to do factor analysis in settings where test/questionnaire data has already been collected and a method for getting scores from those data is required. It is intended to provide students with the requisite skills to deal with this kind of problem in their own research. Topics include: basics of matrix algebra, distinguishing among different factor models (e.g., principal components, principal axis), methods of factor scoring, assessing goodness of fit, how and why to rotate a factor solution, how to deal with dichotomous and ordered categorical (e.g., Likert) data, and special issues that arise in cross-group and cross-cultural applications (e.g., floor and ceiling effects, measurement invariance). Class time is split between 1/3 theoretical discussion and 2/3 hands-on examples using STATA and R statistical software. Readings will be drawn from journal articles. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/RESCH-GE_2016.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------          At Stern IOMS:       GB 4310.01 Statistics for Social Data; meets Wednesdays 2:00-5:00pm. Instructor: Patrick Perry    Statistical methods for describing and utilizing nontraditional data modalities arising from social processes. Half of the course will be devoted to network data (communications, recommendations, and transactions) and the other half will be devoted to textual data (words, phrases, and documents). We will survey a broad class of models for dealing with these types of data. Possible topics include the following: word-sense disambiguation; sentiment analysis; Markov and hidden Markov text models; topic discovery; descriptive statistics for networks; community detection; exponential random graph models; latent space models; network sampling; point processes; low-rank matrix approximations; power laws. See here for a syllabus. Contact pperry@stern.nyu.edu for more details.       -----------------------------------------------------------------------       SPRING 2014:          APSTA-GE 2094 Factor Analysis and Structural Equation Modeling (3 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Spring 2014; Wednesdays 3:30-6:10pm. Course provides students with the software skills and theoretical knowledge required to apply structural equation modeling (SEM). First, we review of multiple regression and basic concepts from matrix algebra. Next, path analysis and factor analysis are developed, leading to more advanced topics, including how to translate theory into models, strategies for dealing with poor fitting specifications, categorical data, and issues in multigroup analysis. The latter component focuses on data applications of SEM, including a final project. Example material will be drawn from education and psychology. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA-GE_2094_Sp2014.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------      APSTA-GE 2997 Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research: Generalized Linear Models (2 points) Instructor: Ying Lu Spring 2014; F 9:30-12:30 (course meets the second half of the term) This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples are drawn from broad areas of health and policy research including determinants of self-reported health status or factors influencing number of clinic visits. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA_2997_syllabus_2014.pdf            12.7.12: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2013       NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2004 Advanced Modeling I: Topics in Multivariate Analysis meets Tuesdays 3:30-6:00pm, Jan 29-Mar 12 (one hour lab follows lecture). Instructor: Peter Halpin.    This year, STRUCTURAL EQUATION MODELS ARE EMPHASIZED. Examines some of the more advanced topics in multivariate data analysis for the behavioral, social, and health sciences. The focus is structural equation modeling with latent variables, although we build up to this topic by considering path analysis, principal components analysis, exploratory factor analysis, and confirmatory factor analysis. Other topics are also surveyed (e.g., MANOVA). The software package STATA is used to give students hands-on experience with analyzing data using the methods covered in class. In so doing, the course provides skills and knowledge critical to those graduate students whose research relies on the analysis of quantitative data. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2042.    12.7.12: Courses offered biennially, offered THIS Spring 2013    NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2011 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods: Classification & Clustering. Meets Fri 9:30am-12:00pm (course begins Mar 26). Instructor: Marc Scott.     Classification and clustering are important statistical techniques commonly applied in many social and behavioral science research problems. Both seek to understand social phenomena through the identification of naturally occurring homogeneous groupings within a population. Classification techniques are used to sort new observations into pre-existing or known groupings, while clustering techniques sort the population under study into groupings based on their observed characteristics. They are sometimes referred to as supervised and unsupervised learning. This course will introduce the student to both techniques, emphasizing visualization, algorithms and models, particulalry for clustering, including the latent class model known as Nagin clusters. May be taken concurrently with any of the other offerings. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2011.       NYU Course # PSYCH-GA 2248 Analysis of Change. Monday 12:00-1:50PM (lecture); Lab session TBA Instructor Patrick Shrout.  This course will review current issues and methods involving the analysis of change in the behavioral and social sciences. Starting from classical methods for the analysis of change (change scores, mixed model ANOVA, regression and MANOVA), we examine the rationale and utility of newer methods: Generalized estimating equations (GEE), Latent change approaches, Hierarchical linear (multilevel) models, and survival analysis. The methods will be introduced conceptually and will be illustrated using real and simulated data. Prior year's syllabus available here: http://www.psych.nyu.edu/couples/Shrout/Syllabi/index.html    NYU Course # SOC-GA 3306 Event History Analysis. Meets Weds 6:20-9PM. Instructor: Lawrence Wu.    This course surveys methods for analyzing event history data, with a focus on continuous-time models and estimation techniques. Topics include the exploratory analysis of event history data, nonparametric methods, right censoring, maximum likelihood estimation, alternative specifications for a time dependent baseline hazard rate, observed and unobserved heterogeneity, time-varying covariates, proportional and nonproportional models, multiple transition and competing risk models, left truncation and left censoring, and analogs of recursive and nonrecursive models. Major emphasis is placed on the logic, practical use, and estimation of models. Prior syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/SOC-GA-3306_syl.pdf    12.6.12: [NYC/Columbia Univ.] META-ANALYSIS COURSE - Spring 2013    TC Course # HUDM 5130 Meta-analysis meets Tuesdays 3:00-5:00pm. Instructor: L. Elizabeth Tipton    This course introduces methods for conducting a quantitative research synthesis using meta-analysis. The focus of the course is both practical and methodological and includes background on all parts of the research synthesis process, including: problem formulation, conducting a literature search, data evaluation, effect size coding, data analysis, and reporting the results. Additionally, the statistical methods used for summarizing the effects found in a study (effect sizes) and for combining the results of these studies under different models (meta-analysis) are introduced and developed. Contact tipton@tc.columbia.edu for more details.       12.3.11: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2012    Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research (Biostatistics III)    NYU Course # RESCH-GE.2997 Meets Mondays, 4:45 – 7:35pm 3 points    This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples include health status, number of clinic visits, etc. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses.    Current syllabus here .    Please contact the course instructor, Ying Lu (ying.lu@nyu.edu) with any questions.    Measurement: Modern Test Theory    NYU Course # APSY-GE.2141 Meets Wednesdays, 3:30 – 6:10pm 3 points    All graduate students from all schools are welcome to enroll. Course requires comfort with introductory statistics and a willingness to learn some statistical programming.    Examines the principles of psychological measurement and testing and the technical interpretation of test scores using modern test models, including Item Response Theory, with an emphasis on the Rasch model. Considers matters of reliability and validity as related to modern test theory. Emphasizes the application of test theory to computerized and/or adaptive testing. Utilizes statistical software to conduct analyses. This course is recommended for anyone with an interest in developing, evaluating and analyzing surveys and assessments related to education, the social sciences, and medicine. Recent syllabus here ; flyer here .    Please contact the course instructor, Jeffrey Steedle (jsteedle@nyu.edu) with any questions. The course is centered on several active research projects in Bayesian computing. News - PRIISM - NYU Steinhardt                                                                         NYU Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development       PRIISM Center for the Promotion of Research Involving Innovative Statistical Methodology                                      News                                                                   10.15.13: New volume published: "Sage Handbook of Multilevel Modeling," edited by PRIISM Co-Director, M. Scott, NYU Stern Prof. J. Simonoff & LSU Prof. B. Marx, with c ontributions by PRIISM Center faculty: J. Buckley, M. Harada, Co-Director J. Hill, M. Scott, Z. Townsend, S. Weinberg, and NYU Psychology Prof. P. Shrout. More details given here .    8.28.13: New/updated applied statistical methods courses of interest to the PRIISM Center community offered Fall 2013/Spring 2014    The PRIISM Center would like to highlight two new courses being offered Fall 2013 and two being offered Spring 2014 that may be of interest to you or your students.       FALL 2013 :    RESCH-GE 2016 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods – Factor Scoring and Practical Issues in Scaling (Informal title, "Measurement in the Trenches" -- 2 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Fall 2013; Mondays 4:55-7:35pm; course runs in the second half of the term, beginning Oct. 29. This course was created in response to inquiries from students and faculty regarding methodological challenges with measurement and scaling. It expands on the topics of measurement and reliability discussed in introductory courses. The focus is how to do factor analysis in settings where test/questionnaire data has already been collected and a method for getting scores from those data is required. It is intended to provide students with the requisite skills to deal with this kind of problem in their own research. Topics include: basics of matrix algebra, distinguishing among different factor models (e.g., principal components, principal axis), methods of factor scoring, assessing goodness of fit, how and why to rotate a factor solution, how to deal with dichotomous and ordered categorical (e.g., Likert) data, and special issues that arise in cross-group and cross-cultural applications (e.g., floor and ceiling effects, measurement invariance). Class time is split between 1/3 theoretical discussion and 2/3 hands-on examples using STATA and R statistical software. Readings will be drawn from journal articles. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/RESCH-GE_2016.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------          At Stern IOMS:       GB 4310.01 Statistics for Social Data; meets Wednesdays 2:00-5:00pm. Instructor: Patrick Perry    Statistical methods for describing and utilizing nontraditional data modalities arising from social processes. Half of the course will be devoted to network data (communications, recommendations, and transactions) and the other half will be devoted to textual data (words, phrases, and documents). We will survey a broad class of models for dealing with these types of data. Possible topics include the following: word-sense disambiguation; sentiment analysis; Markov and hidden Markov text models; topic discovery; descriptive statistics for networks; community detection; exponential random graph models; latent space models; network sampling; point processes; low-rank matrix approximations; power laws. See here for a syllabus. Contact pperry@stern.nyu.edu for more details.       -----------------------------------------------------------------------       SPRING 2014:          APSTA-GE 2094 Factor Analysis and Structural Equation Modeling (3 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Spring 2014; Wednesdays 3:30-6:10pm. Course provides students with the software skills and theoretical knowledge required to apply structural equation modeling (SEM). First, we review of multiple regression and basic concepts from matrix algebra. Next, path analysis and factor analysis are developed, leading to more advanced topics, including how to translate theory into models, strategies for dealing with poor fitting specifications, categorical data, and issues in multigroup analysis. The latter component focuses on data applications of SEM, including a final project. Example material will be drawn from education and psychology. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA-GE_2094_Sp2014.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------      APSTA-GE 2997 Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research: Generalized Linear Models (2 points) Instructor: Ying Lu Spring 2014; F 9:30-12:30 (course meets the second half of the term) This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples are drawn from broad areas of health and policy research including determinants of self-reported health status or factors influencing number of clinic visits. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA_2997_syllabus_2014.pdf            12.7.12: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2013       NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2004 Advanced Modeling I: Topics in Multivariate Analysis meets Tuesdays 3:30-6:00pm, Jan 29-Mar 12 (one hour lab follows lecture). Instructor: Peter Halpin.    This year, STRUCTURAL EQUATION MODELS ARE EMPHASIZED. Examines some of the more advanced topics in multivariate data analysis for the behavioral, social, and health sciences. The focus is structural equation modeling with latent variables, although we build up to this topic by considering path analysis, principal components analysis, exploratory factor analysis, and confirmatory factor analysis. Other topics are also surveyed (e.g., MANOVA). The software package STATA is used to give students hands-on experience with analyzing data using the methods covered in class. In so doing, the course provides skills and knowledge critical to those graduate students whose research relies on the analysis of quantitative data. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2042.    12.7.12: Courses offered biennially, offered THIS Spring 2013    NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2011 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods: Classification & Clustering. Meets Fri 9:30am-12:00pm (course begins Mar 26). Instructor: Marc Scott.     Classification and clustering are important statistical techniques commonly applied in many social and behavioral science research problems. Both seek to understand social phenomena through the identification of naturally occurring homogeneous groupings within a population. Classification techniques are used to sort new observations into pre-existing or known groupings, while clustering techniques sort the population under study into groupings based on their observed characteristics. They are sometimes referred to as supervised and unsupervised learning. This course will introduce the student to both techniques, emphasizing visualization, algorithms and models, particulalry for clustering, including the latent class model known as Nagin clusters. May be taken concurrently with any of the other offerings. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2011.       NYU Course # PSYCH-GA 2248 Analysis of Change. Monday 12:00-1:50PM (lecture); Lab session TBA Instructor Patrick Shrout.  This course will review current issues and methods involving the analysis of change in the behavioral and social sciences. Starting from classical methods for the analysis of change (change scores, mixed model ANOVA, regression and MANOVA), we examine the rationale and utility of newer methods: Generalized estimating equations (GEE), Latent change approaches, Hierarchical linear (multilevel) models, and survival analysis. The methods will be introduced conceptually and will be illustrated using real and simulated data. Prior year's syllabus available here: http://www.psych.nyu.edu/couples/Shrout/Syllabi/index.html    NYU Course # SOC-GA 3306 Event History Analysis. Meets Weds 6:20-9PM. Instructor: Lawrence Wu.    This course surveys methods for analyzing event history data, with a focus on continuous-time models and estimation techniques. Topics include the exploratory analysis of event history data, nonparametric methods, right censoring, maximum likelihood estimation, alternative specifications for a time dependent baseline hazard rate, observed and unobserved heterogeneity, time-varying covariates, proportional and nonproportional models, multiple transition and competing risk models, left truncation and left censoring, and analogs of recursive and nonrecursive models. Major emphasis is placed on the logic, practical use, and estimation of models. Prior syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/SOC-GA-3306_syl.pdf    12.6.12: [NYC/Columbia Univ.] META-ANALYSIS COURSE - Spring 2013    TC Course # HUDM 5130 Meta-analysis meets Tuesdays 3:00-5:00pm. Instructor: L. Elizabeth Tipton    This course introduces methods for conducting a quantitative research synthesis using meta-analysis. The focus of the course is both practical and methodological and includes background on all parts of the research synthesis process, including: problem formulation, conducting a literature search, data evaluation, effect size coding, data analysis, and reporting the results. Additionally, the statistical methods used for summarizing the effects found in a study (effect sizes) and for combining the results of these studies under different models (meta-analysis) are introduced and developed. Contact tipton@tc.columbia.edu for more details.       12.3.11: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2012    Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research (Biostatistics III)    NYU Course # RESCH-GE.2997 Meets Mondays, 4:45 – 7:35pm 3 points    This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples include health status, number of clinic visits, etc. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses.    Current syllabus here .    Please contact the course instructor, Ying Lu (ying.lu@nyu.edu) with any questions.    Measurement: Modern Test Theory    NYU Course # APSY-GE.2141 Meets Wednesdays, 3:30 – 6:10pm 3 points    All graduate students from all schools are welcome to enroll. Course requires comfort with introductory statistics and a willingness to learn some statistical programming.    Examines the principles of psychological measurement and testing and the technical interpretation of test scores using modern test models, including Item Response Theory, with an emphasis on the Rasch model. Considers matters of reliability and validity as related to modern test theory. Emphasizes the application of test theory to computerized and/or adaptive testing. Utilizes statistical software to conduct analyses. This course is recommended for anyone with an interest in developing, evaluating and analyzing surveys and assessments related to education, the social sciences, and medicine. Recent syllabus here ; flyer here .    Please contact the course instructor, Jeffrey Steedle (jsteedle@nyu.edu) with any questions.    A listing of applied statistics courses (and many syllabi) offered at Steinhardt and related departments at NYU is given here , here and here .       9.2.11: [NYC/Columbia Univ.] BAYESIAN COMPUTING COURSE - Fall 2011 Andrew Gelman , Columbia University Professor of Statistics & Political Science, will be teaching a graduate seminar this fall that might be of interest to students. The course is centered on several active research projects in Bayesian computing. More details given here .    8.28.13: New/updated applied statistical methods courses of interest to the PRIISM Center community offered Fall 2013/Spring 2014    The PRIISM Center would like to highlight two new courses being offered Fall 2013 and two being offered Spring 2014 that may be of interest to you or your students.       FALL 2013 :    RESCH-GE 2016 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods – Factor Scoring and Practical Issues in Scaling (Informal title, "Measurement in the Trenches" -- 2 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Fall 2013; Mondays 4:55-7:35pm; course runs in the second half of the term, beginning Oct. 29. This course was created in response to inquiries from students and faculty regarding methodological challenges with measurement and scaling. It expands on the topics of measurement and reliability discussed in introductory courses. The focus is how to do factor analysis in settings where test/questionnaire data has already been collected and a method for getting scores from those data is required. It is intended to provide students with the requisite skills to deal with this kind of problem in their own research. Topics include: basics of matrix algebra, distinguishing among different factor models (e.g., principal components, principal axis), methods of factor scoring, assessing goodness of fit, how and why to rotate a factor solution, how to deal with dichotomous and ordered categorical (e.g., Likert) data, and special issues that arise in cross-group and cross-cultural applications (e.g., floor and ceiling effects, measurement invariance). Class time is split between 1/3 theoretical discussion and 2/3 hands-on examples using STATA and R statistical software. Readings will be drawn from journal articles. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/RESCH-GE_2016.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------          At Stern IOMS:       GB 4310.01 Statistics for Social Data; meets Wednesdays 2:00-5:00pm. Instructor: Patrick Perry    Statistical methods for describing and utilizing nontraditional data modalities arising from social processes. Half of the course will be devoted to network data (communications, recommendations, and transactions) and the other half will be devoted to textual data (words, phrases, and documents). We will survey a broad class of models for dealing with these types of data. Possible topics include the following: word-sense disambiguation; sentiment analysis; Markov and hidden Markov text models; topic discovery; descriptive statistics for networks; community detection; exponential random graph models; latent space models; network sampling; point processes; low-rank matrix approximations; power laws. See here for a syllabus. Contact pperry@stern.nyu.edu for more details.       -----------------------------------------------------------------------       SPRING 2014:          APSTA-GE 2094 Factor Analysis and Structural Equation Modeling (3 points) Instructor: Peter Halpin Spring 2014; Wednesdays 3:30-6:10pm. Course provides students with the software skills and theoretical knowledge required to apply structural equation modeling (SEM). First, we review of multiple regression and basic concepts from matrix algebra. Next, path analysis and factor analysis are developed, leading to more advanced topics, including how to translate theory into models, strategies for dealing with poor fitting specifications, categorical data, and issues in multigroup analysis. The latter component focuses on data applications of SEM, including a final project. Example material will be drawn from education and psychology. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA-GE_2094_Sp2014.pdf       -----------------------------------------------------------------------      APSTA-GE 2997 Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research: Generalized Linear Models (2 points) Instructor: Ying Lu Spring 2014; F 9:30-12:30 (course meets the second half of the term) This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples are drawn from broad areas of health and policy research including determinants of self-reported health status or factors influencing number of clinic visits. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses. Syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/APSTA_2997_syllabus_2014.pdf            12.7.12: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2013       NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2004 Advanced Modeling I: Topics in Multivariate Analysis meets Tuesdays 3:30-6:00pm, Jan 29-Mar 12 (one hour lab follows lecture). Instructor: Peter Halpin.    This year, STRUCTURAL EQUATION MODELS ARE EMPHASIZED. Examines some of the more advanced topics in multivariate data analysis for the behavioral, social, and health sciences. The focus is structural equation modeling with latent variables, although we build up to this topic by considering path analysis, principal components analysis, exploratory factor analysis, and confirmatory factor analysis. Other topics are also surveyed (e.g., MANOVA). The software package STATA is used to give students hands-on experience with analyzing data using the methods covered in class. In so doing, the course provides skills and knowledge critical to those graduate students whose research relies on the analysis of quantitative data. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2042.    12.7.12: Courses offered biennially, offered THIS Spring 2013    NYU Course # RESCH-GE 2011 Advanced Topics in Quantitative Methods: Classification & Clustering. Meets Fri 9:30am-12:00pm (course begins Mar 26). Instructor: Marc Scott.     Classification and clustering are important statistical techniques commonly applied in many social and behavioral science research problems. Both seek to understand social phenomena through the identification of naturally occurring homogeneous groupings within a population. Classification techniques are used to sort new observations into pre-existing or known groupings, while clustering techniques sort the population under study into groupings based on their observed characteristics. They are sometimes referred to as supervised and unsupervised learning. This course will introduce the student to both techniques, emphasizing visualization, algorithms and models, particulalry for clustering, including the latent class model known as Nagin clusters. May be taken concurrently with any of the other offerings. Pairs naturally with RESCH-GE 2011.       NYU Course # PSYCH-GA 2248 Analysis of Change. Monday 12:00-1:50PM (lecture); Lab session TBA Instructor Patrick Shrout.  This course will review current issues and methods involving the analysis of change in the behavioral and social sciences. Starting from classical methods for the analysis of change (change scores, mixed model ANOVA, regression and MANOVA), we examine the rationale and utility of newer methods: Generalized estimating equations (GEE), Latent change approaches, Hierarchical linear (multilevel) models, and survival analysis. The methods will be introduced conceptually and will be illustrated using real and simulated data. Prior year's syllabus available here: http://www.psych.nyu.edu/couples/Shrout/Syllabi/index.html    NYU Course # SOC-GA 3306 Event History Analysis. Meets Weds 6:20-9PM. Instructor: Lawrence Wu.    This course surveys methods for analyzing event history data, with a focus on continuous-time models and estimation techniques. Topics include the exploratory analysis of event history data, nonparametric methods, right censoring, maximum likelihood estimation, alternative specifications for a time dependent baseline hazard rate, observed and unobserved heterogeneity, time-varying covariates, proportional and nonproportional models, multiple transition and competing risk models, left truncation and left censoring, and analogs of recursive and nonrecursive models. Major emphasis is placed on the logic, practical use, and estimation of models. Prior syllabus here: http://steinhardt.nyu.edu/scmsAdmin/media/users/ms184/SOC-GA-3306_syl.pdf    12.6.12: [NYC/Columbia Univ.] META-ANALYSIS COURSE - Spring 2013    TC Course # HUDM 5130 Meta-analysis meets Tuesdays 3:00-5:00pm. Instructor: L. Elizabeth Tipton    This course introduces methods for conducting a quantitative research synthesis using meta-analysis. The focus of the course is both practical and methodological and includes background on all parts of the research synthesis process, including: problem formulation, conducting a literature search, data evaluation, effect size coding, data analysis, and reporting the results. Additionally, the statistical methods used for summarizing the effects found in a study (effect sizes) and for combining the results of these studies under different models (meta-analysis) are introduced and developed. Contact tipton@tc.columbia.edu for more details.       12.3.11: New/updated applied statistical methods courses offered Spring 2012    Advanced Data Analysis in Health and Policy Research (Biostatistics III)    NYU Course # RESCH-GE.2997 Meets Mondays, 4:45 – 7:35pm 3 points    This course is a second year course in advanced statistical techniques that covers useful quantitative tools in health and policy research. Assuming a strong foundation in regression and the general linear model, this course focuses on data analysis that utilizes models for categorical, discrete or limited outcomes that are commonly seen in health and policy studies. Examples include health status, number of clinic visits, etc. In this course students will also learn the principles of likelihood-based inference, which will assist them in some of the more advanced statistics courses.    Current syllabus here .    Please contact the course instructor, Ying Lu (ying.lu@nyu.edu) with any questions.    Measurement: Modern Test Theory    NYU Course # APSY-GE.2141 Meets Wednesdays, 3:30 – 6:10pm 3 points    All graduate students from all schools are welcome to enroll. Course requires comfort with introductory statistics and a willingness to learn some statistical programming.    Examines the principles of psychological measurement and testing and the technical interpretation of test scores using modern test models, including Item Response Theory, with an emphasis on the Rasch model. Considers matters of reliability and validity as related to modern test theory. Emphasizes the application of test theory to computerized and/or adaptive testing. Utilizes statistical software to conduct analyses. This course is recommended for anyone with an interest in developing, evaluating and analyzing surveys and assessments related to education, the social sciences, and medicine. Recent syllabus here ; flyer here .    Please contact the course instructor, Jeffrey Steedle (jsteedle@nyu.edu) with any questions.
